==Old English==
===Etymology===
From Germanic ''*eƀuraz'', from Indo-European ''*epəros''.  Cognate with Old Saxon [[eƀur]] (Dutch [[ever]]), Old High German [[ebur]] (German [[Eber]]), Old Norse [[jǫfurr]].

===Pronunciation===
[[IPA]]: /'eover/

===Noun===
'''eofor''' ''m''

# a [[boar]]; a wild boar
#:''sele ðu him flæsc eoferes'': give him boar’s flesh.

